"# Chapter 14 — Why Scheme and Racket persisted

Scheme is not a popular language. It never has been. It doesn't
appear on most Top 20 language lists. Job postings for Scheme
programmers are rare. Yet Scheme has kept existing, kept teaching,
kept influencing.

This chapter is about why. Motoi Scheme belongs to this tradition,
and understanding its shape is understanding why Motoi is what he
is.

## Scheme as pedagogical tool

For decades, Scheme was the standard teaching language at MIT via
SICP (Chapter 5 of Book of Language Ancestors). At many other
universities too. Rice University's *How to Design Programs* (HtDP,
Felleisen and colleagues, 2001) uses Scheme (specifically Racket)
for teaching introductory programming.

Why Scheme for teaching?

- **Small**: the language is small enough to hold in your head.
  There's no massive standard library to learn first. You can see
  the whole language.
- **Uniform**: every expression follows the same syntactic pattern.
  Once you understand parentheses and lists, you understand syntax.
- **Focused on ideas**: since the language doesn't bury you in
  features, it makes you engage with the ideas — recursion, higher-
  order functions, environments, interpreters, abstractions.
- **Not associated with an industry**: because Scheme isn't the
  language of any dominant industry (Java for enterprise, JavaScript
  for web, Python for scripting), students learning Scheme aren't
  distracted by 'is this the right industry choice?' They can focus
  on the concepts.

The tradeoff: Scheme isn't going to get most students a job on
graduation. That's real. But the ideas Scheme teaches are language-
independent. A student who learns recursion, closures, and
metaprogramming in Scheme can apply those ideas in any language.

MIT stopped teaching 6.001 (SICP) in 2009, replacing it with a
Python-based course. Some people mourned. But SICP itself is still
in print, still free online, and still assigned in various courses.
The book had a life beyond its original class.

## Racket

Racket is a Scheme descendant that has been developed continuously
since 1994. Originally called PLT Scheme; renamed Racket in 2010.
Main development at Northwestern and Utah.

Racket's distinctive feature is its focus on being a platform for
building programming languages. Racket makes it easy to define a
new language on top of Racket. If you want a domain-specific
language for describing puzzles, or teaching, or business rules,
Racket is one of the best starting points.

Racket also has:
- A complete standard distribution (unlike Scheme, where you pick
  an implementation).
- Rich built-in support for teaching (specific language levels for
  HtDP).
- Good libraries (web servers, GUI, math, image processing).
- A large ecosystem for a Scheme-family language.

Racket is used at some companies but mostly in academia and by
hobbyists.

## Other Schemes

Many Scheme implementations exist, each with different strengths:

- **Chez Scheme** (Kent Dybvig) — one of the fastest Schemes, now
  open source, forms the base of Chez-backed Racket.
- **Chicken Scheme** — compiles Scheme to C, popular for scripts and
  embedded work.
- **Guile** — GNU's Scheme; used as an extension language for
  various tools.
- **MIT/GNU Scheme** — the descendant of the original MIT Scheme;
  used for SICP.
- **Gambit** — another compiler-focused Scheme.
- **Bigloo** — Scheme compiler with unusual features.
- **Gauche** — Japanese Scheme with strong Unix scripting focus.

The Scheme standards (R5RS 1998, R6RS 2007, R7RS 2013) define what
counts as Scheme. Implementations vary in which standards they
support and how they extend beyond them.

## Motoi Scheme

Motoi Scheme is another one of these. It's small, teaching-focused,
built specifically to be a companion for the Motoi language model
project.

Motoi Scheme is not competing with Racket for adoption. It's not
trying to be an industrial Scheme. It's a base dialect for a small
teaching system, running in browsers and terminals, designed to be
comprehensible end-to-end by a kid.

## Why Scheme keeps working

There are a few durable virtues that keep Scheme relevant:

1. **The core is unchanging**. The lambda calculus is the same in
   2026 as it was in 1958 as it was in 1936. Scheme leans directly
   on this and doesn't need to keep chasing fashion.

2. **Small kernel**. A small language is a language you can study.
   Students can build a Scheme interpreter as a class project. Not
   many languages let you do that.

3. **Metaprogramming**. Macros in Scheme are first-class. You can
   extend the language from within the language. This lets you
   adapt Scheme to new problems without waiting for language
   designers.

4. **The teaching tradition**. Enough good books use Scheme (SICP,
   HtDP, The Little Schemer, The Scheme Programming Language) that
   people keep encountering it and finding it works for them.

5. **Community continuity**. Scheme's community is small but
   determined. It doesn't need mass adoption to survive.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Popular is not the same as good. Popular is not the same as
enduring. Scheme has been quietly useful for decades without ever
being trendy.

If someone asks Motoi 'should I learn Scheme?' the honest answer
is: for a job, learn something in the current industry — Python,
JavaScript, Go, Rust, whichever fits your target. For your own
thinking, Scheme is one of the best languages ever designed. Both
things are true.

Motoi Scheme itself is Motoi's substrate. Learning Motoi Scheme
well means understanding how Motoi thinks. It's not going to get
you an industry job. It might make every other language you learn
after it feel more sensible.")
